[2]
Date: Mon 21 Nov 2005
From: Mertyn Malkinson <malkins@agri.huji.ac.il>
Source: NY Times, 20 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/20/weekinreview/20basics.html?
emc=eta1&pagewanted=print>

How to Vaccinate 14 Billion Birds
---------------------------------
14 billion. That's how many ducks and chickens are produced in China
every year. To vaccinate all those birds against avian flu, as the
government announced last week [3rd week November 2005] that it was
planning to do, would require about 550 million injections a week.
Sound daunting? Here's another number: 1.3 billion. With 1/5th of the
world's population, China has no shortage of people to accomplish the
task.
G. Donald Ritter, director of health services for Mountaire Farms, a
large poultry producer based in Selbyville, Del., said that, if any
country could inoculate all its poultry, China was it. "It's labor
intensive," he said of the process. "But they've got more people and
labor than anybody."
China has had more than 60 outbreaks of avian influenza among poultry
in the last 2 years. While a widespread vaccination program can help
control outbreaks, the usual procedure in most countries is "cull and
quarantine," killing all birds within a few miles of the affected
area and quarantining all others in a larger area.
Dr. Ritter, who was among a group of veterinarians and scientists sent by the
United States to Beijing 2 weeks ago [1st week of November 2005] to discuss
poultry health issues, said that birds would be injected at about 2 weeks of
age, followed by a booster shot 4 weeks later.
The usual dose is 1/4 to 1/2 a milliliter, so millions of liters of
vaccine will be required. "They can gear up to make tremendous
quantities," Dr. Ritter said. "And it's not tremendously expensive."
The process of injecting the birds is straightforward. "You pen them off," he
said. "And then you work them against the pen, pick them up, [inject] them and
throw them" outside the pen. In the United States, he said, breeder chickens
are vaccinated in this way (for other diseases, not for avian flu); a crew of
about 6 people with vaccine guns can inject about 10 000 birds in 3 hours. At
that level of efficiency, at least 10 000 workers would be needed to vaccinate
China's birds [compared with Viet Nam's estimate of 100 000 vaccinators for
their much smaller country -- see [1] above. - Mod.JW].
But the Chinese program will be nowhere near that efficient.
Vaccinations are easiest in large poultry houses; the workers can
move the pen through the building, methodically injecting every bird
along the way. Most of China's birds are in small flocks in villages,
and often are running loose. "The door-to-door stuff is going to
require more manpower," Dr. Ritter said. "But they've got enough
people to do it. They just need to fan out within the village." And
then come back 4 weeks later and do it again.
[Byline: Henry Fountain]
--
Mertyn Malkinson
Rehovot 76470
