[It is impossible to predict if the pessimism in [1] above, or the more
optimistic expectations expressed by Dr Ritter in [2], will prevail. There are
several main optional action schemes which HPAI-affected countries may apply
when the control or eradication of HPAI within their territories is
contemplated:
1. Stamping out* without vaccination.
2. Modified stamping out* without vaccination.
3. Stamping out combined with selective vaccination.
4. Modified stamping out combined with selective vaccination.
5. Modified stamping out combined with mass vaccination.
6. Mass vaccination combined with selective biosecurity measures.
(*The definition of stamping-out policy, according to chapter 1.1.1
("General definitions") in OIE's Terrestrial Animal Health Code (2005
edition), is:
"carrying out under the authority of the Veterinary Administration,
on confirmation of a disease, the killing of the animals which are
affected and those suspected of being affected in the herd and, where
appropriate, those in other herds which have been exposed to
infection by direct animal to animal contact, or by indirect contact
of a kind likely to cause the transmission of the causal pathogen.
All susceptible animals, vaccinated or unvaccinated, on an infected
premises should be killed and their carcasses destroyed by burning or
burial, or by any other method which will eliminate the spread of
infection through the carcasses or products of the animals killed.
This policy should be accompanied by the cleansing and disinfection procedures
defined in this Terrestrial Code.
The term "Modified stamping-out policy" should be used in communications to
the OIE whenever the above animal health measures are not implemented in full
and details of the modifications should be given".
While stamping out may involve, in addition to the affected premises,
also the killing of animals in other sites (e.g. within a prescribed
radius around the affected premises, or in-contacts in other
locations), modified stamping out will include the killing of the
affected flocks/herds or affected animals only, applying other, less
severe measures in relation to unaffected in-contacts or
adjacent/close holdings. Generally, stamping out policy is combined
with non-vaccination policy, while modified stamping out is applied
when vaccination is allowed or prescribed. Vaccination may be
geographically restricted or general.)
All the above 6 schemes must include the application of surveillance
and basic, crucial biosecurity measures (quarantine of infected
holdings, movement and transportation restrictions within areas to be
defined, cleansing/disinfection etc). Additional variations may be
considered, such as the use of DIVA (Differentiating Infected from
Vaccinated Animals) strategy; see in 20050307.0680, 20030428.1047.
A key international meeting, addres
sing the Global Strategy for the Progressive Control of Highly Pathogenic
Avian Influenza (HPAI), was convened by FAO, OIE , WHO and the World Bank in
Geneva during the second week of November 2005. The 600 participants from 100
countries discussed a strategy paper prepared by FAO and OIE, within the
umbrella of the global framework for the control of transboundary animal
diseases (GF-TADs), and in collaboration with WHO; the said document is
available at
<http://www.fao.org/ag/againfo/subjects/documents/ai/HPAIGlobalStrategy31Oct05.
pdf>.
Prepared before the publication of the first reported human AI cases
in China, the said document includes the following text in article
3.3.1.4 which deals with the situation in P.R.China -- indicating the
recommended disease-control strategy there:
"China experienced HPAI infection well before the current crisis began in late
2003 and early 2004. It has not reported any human cases, but has a vast duck
population that acts as a source of infection for terrestrial poultry. China
is vaccinating domestic poultry and ducks in high-risk areas, using locally
produced inactivated vaccines, as the principal method of controlling the
disease, given the widespread nature of HPAI in the country. Vaccine efficacy
in ducks appears to be good, with a reportedly significant reduction in virus
shedding.
Within the immediate to medium-term (1-6 years) the current disease control
strategies applied will be improved and consolidated. This will involve
proactive, risk-based surveillance, stamping out, application of biosecurity
measures, and strategic vaccination with well-defined good quality vaccines.
Vaccination of terrestrial poultry will be linked with a well-structured post-
vaccination surveillance programme to provide better information on the
disease dynamics and the impact of increasing flock immunity in domestic
poultry. Further field studies will be carried out to determine the impact of
duck vaccination on the level and duration of virus shedding under field
conditions.
In the medium- to long-term (4-6 years) the disease will be pushed
back into well-defined areas. This will provide an opportunity for
the country to establish disease free compartments to trade safely in
poultry products within 7-10 years."
The new Chinese plan, published after the reporting of human cases
and the further spread of the disease into additional provinces,
seems to take the plan further from strategic vaccination (which
usually involves commercial farms) into mass vaccination (meant to
cover all domestic birds, including small- and backyard holdings).
Such an action should entail the needed post-vaccination surveillance
programme: an additional significant burden.
There is no known precedent to such an ambitious plan. While the required
biosecurity measures by vaccinating teams can be improved, the possible impact
of mass vaccination upon the evolution of new virus strains is a debatable
issue. The response of the international organisations and their experts to
this plan is anticipated with interest. - Mod. AS].
